		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 03/27/03<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.25)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 5, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> NOT FOR REVIEW!!!<br />
=================<br />
<br />
<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
Wow! So what&#39;s new in the Rules World? (= Okay, okay... I guess we&#39;ve all heard about the new Standard format for Lord of the Rings. I&#39;m sure everyone has their own opinion about the format. I see it as nothing more than Fellowship Block vs. Tower Block. This is a new format that we have the option to use. If you don&#39;t want to play in those tournament, then I suggest you don&#39;t play in those tournaments. I understand the complaint about Decipher making the Championship tournaments Standard format, but that is up to them. And if you really want to play in those tournaments, you must accept that as the tournament format. Just as we accepted the fact we can&#39;t play the Ford of Bruinen in Open Format. That being said, I look forward to seeing what decks come out of this new format. Nazgul (which is what I play) certainly looks better!<br />
<br />
Some of you have asked me how much of an influence I had in this. I&#39;m flattered, but I don&#39;t get to make those types of decisions. But I can tell you that if I did make those decisions, my solution would have been much harsher than what Decipher did. I&#39;ve told a few others my suggestions, and they&#39;ve all agreed that Decipher&#39;s decision was better. So just be happy it&#39;s Decipher that&#39;s in charge and not me. (=<br />
<br />
In other news, the Vegas Premier Series Event was a blast! I had a lot of fun seeing so many of you there. I don&#39;t know what the rest of my summer plans look like, but hopefully I can make another Convention this summer. Right now it&#39;s a toss up between ComiCon (which is my first choice) and GenCon/DecipherCon. Hopefully I&#39;ll see you all again soon. (=<br />
<br />
Keep the questions coming and I&#39;ll be back in two weeks.<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
Return home soon, Carlos.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about LOTR Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>If I have two uruks in play against 5 companions, and Faramir is involved in one skirmish and aragorn in another, and the FP player decides to resolve aragorn first, can I play my Savagery on the uruk skirmishing Faramir? [DragonLady]</b><br />
<br />
Correct. As long as you meet the requirements and pay the costs, you can play any skirmish event or special ability in any skirmish. (Or any other phase for that matter.) The trick however is that usually those events and special abilities only last for the duration of that single skirmish phase. The other problem is that they only really work when played for characters in the active skirmish. You can play PATHS (adding a burden) during any skirmish, but it only wounds the minions when it&#39;s the ring-bearers skirmish that&#39;s resolving. Savagery however lasts until the Regroup phase. So eventhough you don&#39;t play it during the active skirmish phase, you still will get the effects when Faramir&#39;s skirimish becomes the active one (thereby getting around Faramir, Son of Denethor&#39;s gametext). <br />
<br />
<b>a couple of questions -- can you spot the (3) cost of Fury of the White Rider, in order to use it, when there is no other twilight in the pool? does a troop of uruk hai negate the discard bonus effect of gwemigil? [Lance Uppercut]</b><br />
<br />
No. You cannot spot (3) if there is no twilight in the pool. This is an example of checking the requirements of an action, before paying the costs. So you would have to spot the (3) already in the twilight pool before you add (3) for the cost of the event.<br />
<br />
Any strength bonus from a weapon card is ignored by the Troop of Uruk-hai. That means that if the symbol or gametext that gives the bonus is printed on a weapon card, the strength bonus is ignored. You can still discard cards from hand and you&#39;d still get the damage +1, but you would not get the strength bonus.<br />
<br />
Please note the difference between Gwemigil and Merry, From O&#39;er the Brandywine or Helm&#39;s Gate. The bonuses from Merry and Helm&#39;s Gate are NOT from weapons.<br />
<br />
<b>In the rulebook, each skirmish is referred to as a separate &quot;skirmish phase&quot;. Does this mean that the (limit +3) of the card Trust Me as You Once Did applies only to each individual skirmish, and that for a single copy of the card, Gandalf can exert to make a companion in each skirmish strength +3? Thanks! [Erithil]</b><br />
<br />
Correct. Each skirmish resolves in it&#39;s own, separate skirmish phase and as such does not fall under the &quot;limit rule&quot;. As long as you can exert, you can get a (+3 max per Trust Me As You Once Did card) strength bonus in as many skirmishes as you want. <br />
<br />
<b>If I play Saruman Servant of the Eye and then put Sarumans staff on him does this now allow me to assign him to a companion? [BaneMalar1]</b><br />
<br />
Correct. Saruman, Servant of the Eye allows you to assign any assignable [Isengard] minion, including himself if he has his staff.<br />
<br />
<b>For Knocked on the Head: If you have an exhausted Merry in play in the regroup phase, can you play a knocked on the head to play a copy of Merry from the discard pile to heal him? [Urthanz]</b><br />
<br />
No. )= You must still obey uniqueness rules. If Merry is already active you may not play another copy of him. The action to spot a wound and discard a unique companion or ally from your hand is only a Fellowship action.  <br />
<br />
<b>Two questions about i&#39;d make you squeak. First of all does this card apply to all wounds on all hobbits, or just the wounds on a specific hobbit? And secondly, if you have two out is the site +6 or does the limit of 3 still apply? thx [Son of Gloin]</b><br />
<br />
Good question. I would say that I&#39;d Make You Squeak triggers off any wound on any hobbit, so if you have 2 wounds on Merry and another on Pippin, the shadow number of each site would be +3 for each active copy of I&#39;d Make You Squeak.<br />
<br />
<b>I have a question about a few cards that deal with assignment. First off, &quot;The End Comes&quot; says spot 5 moria minions during assignment to force the ring-bearer to skirmish. Can you use this card during the fierce phase to force frodo to skirmish the troll? also with common saruman from RotEL, can his ability be used to assign during fierce skirmishes? And finaly with Ents, do you have to exert hobbits twice or discard 2 cards twice to allow them to participate in both normal and fierce skirmishes or will one exertion/discard be sufficient for both of the skirmishes? T.I.A. for your help with these questions. [Blink This]</b><br />
<br />
The assignment phases for normal skirmishes and fierce skirmishes are separate. But they are both assignment phases. So if you want to play The End Comes or uses Saruman&#39;s gametext during the fierce assignment phase, that is fine.<br />
<br />
Because the assignment phases are seperate, you would have to exert a second time or discard a second time in order to allow the Unhasty Ents to be assigned to fierce skirmishs.<br />
<br />
<b>Hey man! Did you check out my TR? Here&#39;s my question. It came up last night playtesting my friend Steve&#39;s new Smeagal deck. When you play that event that discards Smeagal during the maneuver phase to discard a minion, the shadow player may exert any minion twice to prevent this. If I prevent it, does Smeagal still get discarded because discarding Smeagal is the cost of the card? Good question, eh? [Patrick Sullivan]</b><br />
<br />
Sorry I missed the TR. )= Yes, this is a good question. When an effect is cancelled or prevented, the costs of the action must still be paid. So if you discard Smeagol for Be Back Soon, but the effect is cancelled Smeagol must remain discarded.<br />
<br />
<b>Here&#39;s a ringbound ranger question for you: If I have enough Gondorian Rangers out to make the Nazgul roaming at site 5 (say 2 of them) and my opponent plays Bill Ferny...are the Nazgul roaming during the skirmish phase or not? Bill Ferny explicitly says they are not roaming so does that swarthy snearing fella laugh at rangers? [Charles Kerekanich]</b><br />
<br />
Like the Hollin site from Fellowship Block, Ferny makes all Nazgul not roaming regardless of the site number on the minions or the current site. As long as Bill Ferny is still active, none of the cards can make Nazgul roaming. Good for the Shadow player, not so good for the Ring-bound Rangers. (=<br />
<br />
<b>I know ther was something in the old FAQ about how you can&#39;t discard 3 card for They Are Coming unless you can verify that you have an orc in your discard pile. Why is that? And what happens if you try to play Simblemyne but you don&#39;t have anything in your draw deck that you can pull? [DragonLady]</b><br />
<br />
When the effect of an action requires you to play a card from your draw deck, you do not HAVE to play a card. Either because there isn&#39;t a viable card play available or you choose not to play the card. This is because Lord of the Rings does not have a verification rule like Star Wars:CCG. In order to avoid the need for a verification rule, the game is set up so that you don&#39;t have to make a card play if you can&#39;t or choose not to. So if you play Simbelmyne and there isn&#39;t anything to play from your draw deck, the costs are still paid and the card has no effect.<br />
<br />
HOWEVER, if an effect requires you to play a card from your hand or from your discard pile you must play the card. If you can not, you must take back any of the costs that were played. So if you discarded 3 cards from hand to play a [Moria] Orc from your discard pile, but there isn&#39;t an Orc to play, you must return the 3 discarded cards to your hand. (Note: One of the three cards you discard may be a [Moria] Orc to put into play.) Also, if you play Morgul Gates, you must also play a Nazgul from your hand. If you can not, then you must return the Morgul Gates back to your hand. This rule is the result of a degenerative decktype that was created in Mines of Moria. This rule, along with the Rule of 4, were created to prevent this type of deck from ever occuring again.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about LOTR Meta:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>Wow we can ask you meta questions? Hup zah! I&#39;d like to hear your opinion on Uruk Bomb (or Uruks in general). Do you think Saruman should be errated? Or the regular? Or both? What&#39;s your general take on this beast of an archetype? [Nexus X]</b> <br />
<br />
You can ask me meta questions to I guess. I&#39;m just not sure how interesting the opinion of a 1737 rated player, that only gets to play in 1 out of 4 tournaments a month, really is. So just be aware of the person you&#39;re asking for advice from. (=<br />
<br />
My opinion of the Uruk Bomb is that it&#39;s strong. It can be annoying, but to be honest I prefer to play against it rather then to play against Moria Swarm. All cultures have a trick or tactic to them and you have to be prepared to face all of them. All of my decks are prepared to face Uruks and have &quot;extra&quot; cards devoted to handling them. Simply because they are the most popular right now. Not that I win every game I play, but I have not lost to the site 5 bomb in a tournament since my first experience against it. (Back in January.) My fellowship decks are all prepared for Uruks and they all survive. The next thing I need to learn is to stop my opponent&#39;s fellowship too. (=<br />
<br />
In the case of Saruman and the Uruk Regular, I think both are fine as they are. Unfortunately, they are very much like bleach and ammonia. It&#39;s when their mixed together that you have problems. Uruk Regulars have the weakness of being exhausted when you use their ability. One shot from a bow and you no longer have to worry about that minion. Unfortunately, Saruman protects him (like the Uruk Captain) so that his gametext and only weakness can&#39;t be exploited. For Saruman, his weakness is his inability to fight and his reliance on other minions. Saruman really doesn&#39;t do anything unless you have soe Uruks to back him up, but with a twilight cost of 4 it&#39;s difficult to get enough minions out to make him effective. Which is where the Uruk Regular comes in. A couple of Uruk Regulars can more than make up for the 4 Twilight that Saruman costed and are themselves Uruks to take advantage of his gametext. Deep of Helm is just gravy...<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about SW Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>Hello Enrique Huerta, the new light hoth objective says that you can&#39;t lose more than 1 force from everything except battleground drains. Does this mean that Occupations deal only 1 damage, or is every site that is &quot;occupied&quot; resolved seperatly? hope you can help me, [Cedrik]</b> <br />
<br />
Force loss to the Occupation cards (not Endor Occupation) is all done at one time, because the Occupation card is just one card. So if you controlled 4 Tatooine locations, you&#39;d cause 4 Force loss all at once. If the new objectives limit that to 1, then you&#39;d only have to lose 1 Force.<br />
<br />
<b>1. Can you fire this weapon more than once in the control phase. With the text and Sorry about the Mess? &#39;Firing Weapons: generally fire no more than once per battle or attack.&#39; 2. Automatic Modifier. Situation: 2 Star Destroyers control Hoth. DS player has a Imperial Walker 4 power at marker 4. LS player deploys Lando w/Vibro Ax there and Jedi Luke w/LS, LS Pro to Marker 3. LS player initiates against the walker and attempts to play &#39;I&#39;ve got a bad feeling about this&#39;. The card compares power which is not modified +2 until the power segment of the battle, correct? [Dan Waier]</b><br />
<br />
1. Yes.<br />
2. Correct. Total Power is calculated (and modified) during the Power Segment of a battle, which is after all battle actions have been played. <br />
<br />
<b>If Commander Luke is in Rouge 1 at the Wattos Junkyard, does he draw 2 destiny if Watto is present? Junkyard says opponent may not draw and commie Luke says draws 2 if not able to otherwise. Please confirm asap. Thanks in advance! [The Judge]</b><br />
<br />
It has been ruled by the PC - Rules Committee that &quot;unless able to otherwise&quot; is always checked last and always allows the character to draw destiny if no other destinies were drawn (or the minimum was not drawn). So regardless of the gametext that limits other destiny draws, cards that &quot;draw unless able to otherwise&quot; always get to draw their destiny. Commander Luke (V) in Rogue 1 draws 2 destiny at Watto&#39;s Junkyard with Watto there.<br />
<br />
<b>This question is simple. Can a virtual card and the non-virtual version of the same card be in play at the same time if they are non-unique? [anakin1138]</b><br />
<br />
Yes. There are no restrictions to having virtual and non-virtual cards in play at the same time as long as you still obey uniqueness rules.<br />
<br />
<b>Can you replace beedo by another beedo ? Does it text (replaces any male rodian) suspend the personas replacement rule (you can replace a caracter with the same copy) ? [Max]</b><br />
<br />
According to the latest Rulings Update release by the PC - Rules Committee, Beedo only replaces an &quot;other male Rodian&quot;. So Beedo is not able to replace another copy of himself already in play. Beedo does not suspend the persona replace replacement rule in regards to replacing a card with the a copy of the same card.<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
